{"id":"1812.04601","submitter":"Oleg Lychkovskiy","authors":"Oleg Lychkovskiy","title":"A remark on the notion of independence of quantum integrals of motion in\n  the thermodynamic limit","comments":null,"journal-ref":"J. Stat. Phys. 178, 1028 (2020)","doi":"10.1007/s10955-019-02482-2","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Studies of integrable quantum many-body systems have a long history with an\nimpressive record of success. However, surprisingly enough, an unambiguous\ndefinition of quantum integrability remains a matter of an ongoing debate. We\ncontribute to this debate by dwelling upon an important aspect of quantum\nintegrability -- the notion of independence of quantum integrals of motion\n(QIMs). We point out that a widely accepted definition of functional\nindependence of QIMs is flawed, and suggest a new definition. Our study is\nmotivated by the PXP model -- a model of $N$ spins $1/2$ possessing an\nextensive number of binary QIMs. The number of QIMs which are independent\naccording to the common definition turns out to be equal to the number of\nspins, $N$. A common wisdom would then suggest that the system is completely\nintegrable, which is not the case. We discuss the origin of this conundrum and\ndemonstrate how it is resolved when a new definition of independence of QIMs is\nemployed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 11 Dec 2018 18:40:45 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 29 Apr 2019 17:16:42 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 27 Sep 2019 09:25:15 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 24 Dec 2019 16:04:35 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Mon, 3 Feb 2020 12:49:55 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Sun, 16 Feb 2020 11:52:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-02-18"}
